Indonesian President B.J. Habibie has condemned <TIMEX2 val="PAST_REF" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="1998-12-01T05:37:28.57" anchor_dir="BEFORE" comment="">recent</TIMEX2> religious clashes
and appealed for calm. Mr. Habibie <TIMEX2 val="1998-12-01" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">today</TIMEX2> said it was wrong to attack any
house of God and that the government will not tolerate any religious or
ethnic discrimination. On <TIMEX2 val="1998-11-30" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">Monday</TIMEX2>, thousands of Christians rioted in remote
Eastern Indonesia setting fire to mosques and Muslim-owned businesses. No
one was injured in that violence which hit the town of Kupang in West
Timor. The trouble followed a rally by Christians protesting <TIMEX2 val="1998-W48" mod="" set="" non_specific="" anchor_val="" anchor_dir="" comment="">last week</TIMEX2>'s
religious unrest in Jakarta where Muslim youths attacked several churches.
At least 13 people were killed in that outbreak of violence.
